{
  "text": "To assess if there might be changes in eCB release at other synapses onto CA1 pyramidal neurons in Pyr-KO, we examined a well-described eCB-dependent change in shortterm plasticity at GABAergic synapses: depolarization induced suppression of inhibition (DSI) [CITATION_1] . DSI is a consequence of the retrograde effect of depolarizationinduced eCB release from CA1 pyramidal cells on presynaptic GABAergic terminals, leading to a decrease in the amplitude of IPSCs due to less GABA release [CITATION_2] . Remarkably, DSI is intact in Pyr-KO, relative to Pyr-WT (Fig. S7) . Thus, the retrograde effects of eCB release appear to be unaltered at inhibitory, but not excitatory, synapses on to CA1 pyramidal neurons, pointing to a restricted role of PirB at excitatory CA3 to CA1 synapses. Collectively these experiments demonstrate that CB1R function, activation of group I mGluRs, and effects of eCBs at GABAergic synapses are not affected in the absence of PirB. Moreover, they confirm a presynaptic location for CB1 receptors at glutamatergic CA3-CA1 Schaffer collateral synapses [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
